text.0: Regardless of how long it takes to get results, it’s CRUCIAL that you get your information from multiple credible news sources. So, we want to know: where will you get your information on #ElectionNight?
text.1: Remember that polls close at different times in every state. That’ll influence what information is available throughout the night. https://t.co/YIL7IUTuhH
text.2: For real-time, bite-sized updates, check out this Twitter list of trusted #ElectionNight analysts. https://t.co/HkZWop0n1s
text.3: Keep in mind that the best and most unbiased information will come from traditional media sources. Outlets like @AP have been calling races for years and are transparent about their methods. https://t.co/9hBowu4zLS https://t.co/U1YGi8IfWk
text.4: It could be a long night (or week) waiting for #Election2020 results. Here, our colleagues at @PolitiFact break down where to find good information on #ElectionNight. :thread:https://t.co/gmNoauTaEQ https://t.co/C2bGDsW7Kt
text.5:
@JoanLunden’s tip: watch out for emotional reactions. 

If a post or an article makes you angry, makes you laugh out loud, or confirms what you already believe in, you should probably stop and check it out. https://t.co/DUzna8a0kp
text.6:
@camanpour’s second tip: watch out for pink slime. 

Many local news websites -- pink slime journalism -- have popped up this year. Look for authors, bylines, original reporting, ‘about’ pages and article dates to see if a ‘local’ source you’re looking at it legit. https://t.co/ydIvFYzjrz
text.7: Wanna keep up with #Election2020 news on YouTube? Check this out! https://t.co/LFdZ2Z5RQF
text.8:
@CydBee’s tip: be thoughtful when you talk with friends and family who shared misinfo

-Be transparent & stick to the facts
-Recognize you’re upset & let yourself calm down
-Put your relationship w the person first.. 1 on 1 & offline convos are best
-Be nice! https://t.co/nu6xhCp7iQ
text.9: A lot of outlets talk about meeting young people where they are, but @MediaWise walks the walk when it comes to teaching Gen Z about media literacy and fact-checking!! https://t.co/70yWOPtfBV
text.12:
@IAmAmnaNawaz's tip: fact-check before you share.

Misinformation can take a lot of different forms, and sometimes false claims aren’t so obvious. Those SHEG three questions are a realllllyyy good place to start to make sure you don’t pass on bad info. https://t.co/pWoDzPgdxX
text.13:
@smartereveryday’s tip: When you see a claim, ask yourself these three questions - developed by @SHEG_stanford 

1) Who is behind the information?
2) What is the evidence? 
3) What are other sources saying? https://t.co/yv4Rfmic1F
text.14:
@davejorgenson’s tip: know the difference between fact and opinion pieces. 

For news, a reporter researchers facts, interviews sources and delivers info w/o bias. Look out for labels - reputable sources will make it clear what’s an opinion. https://t.co/wxkWwoXviD
text.15:
@SoldierKnowBest’s tip: when you come across something that you disagree with, take a minute to check your emotions. 

Then, decide whether you want to respond. If you do, talking 1 on 1 and offline is best. And stick to the facts! https://t.co/i3vcFGdPyo
text.16:
@hari’s tip: lateral reading.

When you come across a questionable claim, open up multiple tabs and use keyword searches to see what other sources are saying. https://t.co/yuxWioBpON
text.17: We might not get the final #election results tonight, so in the meantime, it's a good idea to sharpen your media literacy skills so you can be on the lookout for misinformation. Luckily, our MediaWise ambassadors got you covered.
text.18: Here's an update on what I've been up to: for the past two months I've been working with college students across the country to produce a 50-part TikTok series teaching first-time voters how to fine reliable information about the #election https://t.co/Rc8FZ5tJVa
text.19: Yes - rinse and repeat. Always get context. https://t.co/avbcUtu9z7
text.20: This is especially important when it comes to sharing #ElectionResults. Make sure you hold off on sharing until 3-4 credible sources are reporting the same thing. https://t.co/DW8Fqw0fkE
text.21: And of course, why it’s important to read multiple sources before sharing. https://t.co/GvDdlh1bAq
text.22: We also focused on teaching some key #medialiteracy  skills. Like the importance of reading past the headline. https://t.co/r4PsSmZes6
text.23: And this claim that if a poll worker marks on your ballot, it will be invalidated. (Also not true.) https://t.co/OCilU3Za6c
text.24: We also looked into claims about #ballots. Here, we fact-checked a claim that postal workers could toss out ballots they didn’t agree with, since mail-in ballots list your party affiliation. (Not True.) https://t.co/Qp0SE79Ig5
text.25: And this video from the #Trump campaign that left out some pretty necessary context. https://t.co/nPvLOFTpYN
text.26: We also fact-checked digitally manipulated media, like this video from the #Biden campaign that spliced together footage of Trump talking about the coronavirus. https://t.co/zGVVvJCiYQ
text.27: In this series, we also fact-checked viral images using reverse image searches. Remember that photo of the sunken boat with a #Trump2020 flag? Yeah, not real. https://t.co/1NrvuxKBKZ
text.28: And these 3 tips we gave for avoiding misinformation related to Trump’s #COVID19 diagnosis are especially useful tonight -- focus on what has been reported as #fact, not the what ifs. https://t.co/9Tb6li8TCz
text.29: Like when some people falsely claimed that “The Simpsons” predicted that President Trump would die from the #coronavirus https://t.co/brBvva9QeB
text.30: This year, election misinformation and #COVID19 misinformation went hand in hand. https://t.co/Z3GKOqjwLx
text.31: And never underestimate the power of a healthy news diet :adult:‍:cooking:. https://t.co/NMuQiLsdR1
text.32: #Voting can be complicated, but not when you have a voter guide walking you through the process. https://t.co/QuJj1JRlJz
text.33: #ElectionDay is finally here! :United_States:For the past 2 months, the MediaWise Campus Correspondents have been working to produce a 50-part TikTok series teaching first-time voters how to find reliable information related to the #2020election - Here’s a look back at some of our favorites:

Pause before you share and check multiple sources to confirm info. When you see a questionable claim, use the SHEG three questions: Who is behind the information? What is the evidence? What are other sources saying? https://t.co/Jt22ukXm3b

text.41: If you did a quick keyword search, you would have seen that MANY states have same-day voter registration. @NCSLorg #Election2020 https://t.co/ZAK5ppAfNl https://t.co/DiWXK3KL6W
text.42: Not so fast! This needs some context. As the article states, @IlhanMN was referring to same-day voter registration in Minnesota. ALWAYS read past the headline and check out MULTIPLE sources to get the full scope of a story. https://t.co/fHfInRF225
text.43:
tldr; BE KIND TODAY! 

Great thread with tips for having difficult conversations about misinformation and politics tonight at home while you wait for results to roll in... https://t.co/Y0BlHWvCgC
text.44: thank you @TomWJones @Poynter for shout out to Mark Shields & @nytdavidbrooks - "I always enjoy watching the civil, respectful and occasionally humorous debates" @NewsHour so lucky to have them on our team this election night
text.45: #ElectionDay is tomorrow. WATCH our #FacetheFacts youth town hall to prepare to spot #misinformation with @mediawise:  https://t.co/hIZ1PWKj9E
text.46:
.@JakeSheridan_ of @mediawise assembled sites that are tracking misinformation so you (or someone you know) doesn't unintentionally share something misleading.

https://t.co/0v5KrR7TEt https://t.co/sdXhHfrJyW
text.47: And if the conversation doesn’t go as planned at first, don’t lose hope. Tough conversations are usually the ones worth having.
text.48: Next, gently ask where they got their information and offer to swap sources. Better yet, load them up with evidence from sources you *know* they trust. Use your sources wisely https://t.co/4oLTMcCMfi
text.49: OK - so difference of opinion is one thing, but what should you do if a loved one is instead sharing misinformation? Here are some tips from Youtube beauty creator and MediaWise Ambassador @cydbee.  First, be transparent and stick to the facts. https://t.co/B3cMCfnxm7
text.50: Try having a conversation *Conversation being the keyword here* When we feel heard, we’re more likely to listen. So, make sure the conversation is a two-way street. https://t.co/SQ93MLGYJP
text.51: Put your relationship with this person first, and reach out privately. Nobody wants to be called out in front of family and friends or in the comments section. https://t.co/UrYAk2GfTA
text.52: Talking about politics can be tricky. And when there are differences at the dinner table, things can get super awkward. While we wait for results to roll in, here are some tips for navigating difficult conversations this #ElectionDay https://t.co/WrOnd8nUao
text.53: Finally, here are a few tips for navigating conversations with friends and family members who are sharing misinformation online. https://t.co/nmqkygdZoi
text.54: PAUSE :pause_button_selector: before you press that share button. There are a couple different indicators to look for :magnifying_glass_tilted_right: to vet information online. https://t.co/mLp5R4zIUT
text.55: REMEMBER: Context is key :key:. Make sure you have the full picture :framed_picture_selector: of the stories you’re reading. Try practicing lateral reading (another @SHEG_Stanford term)  by opening up multiple tabs and reading what different sources are reporting. https://t.co/1g2M5itWDH
text.56: Before you let #Election content on social media influence your point of view, ask yourself these three questions developed by @SHEG_Stanford: https://t.co/oQ7NkJuRPK
text.57: While you’re waiting for results on #ElectionNight (and potentially the next few days), watch these videos :television: to learn how you can avoid misinformation and get the facts on #Election2020 results. https://t.co/52SKXnwFuo
text.58: And finally, here are some things you should be looking for from a news source to determine whether it's a reliable source for #ElectionDay information. If you have a hard time finding these things on their sites that's a red flag! :triangular_flag: https://t.co/ciXN7kbKZ8
text.59: This one is really important! Photos and videos are usually good examples of evidence, HOWEVER, those can be manipulated and used out of context. Use a reverse image search to verify what you're seeing is being used in the proper #ElectionDay context. https://t.co/bxPT1HgtQG
text.60:
Then, MEMORIZE these 3 questions developed by @SHEG_Stanford to help you analyze the content you're seeing online. 

These questions are key in helping determine whether the #ElectionDay information you're seeing is LEGIT :white_heavy_check_mark: or NOT LEGIT :cross_mark: https://t.co/bU8zBgn99Y
text.61:
As you're scrolling your feed you'll likely come across some posts that make you feel emotional. The best thing to do when this happens is to stop :stop_sign::raised_hand: and take a beat. 

It's important to understand that #misinformation and #disinformation tend to appeal to our emotions. https://t.co/dY97M3KswH
text.62: Now is as good a time as any to brush up on some KEY :key: #medialiteracy skills because there will likely be loads of #ElectionDay misinformation in the coming days. First, understand the difference between #misinformation and #disinformation. https://t.co/YHcpIQ9eAt
